'''Juninho Bacuna''' (born 7 August 1997) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[central midfielder]] for {{Dutch football updater|Volendam}} club [[FC Volendam|Volendam]] on loan from Turkish club [[Gaziantep F.K.|Gaziantep]]. Born in the Netherlands, he represents the [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao national team]].

Bacuna began his career in his native Netherlands with [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] before moving to English football with [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. After one season in the [[Premier League]] and two in the second-tier Championship, he spent six months with [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and then returned to English football with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in 2022. He left for Al-Wehda in 2024. In international football, he played for the Netherlands up to [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|under-21 level]] before switching in 2019 to represent Curaçao, for which he qualified by descent.

==Club career==
===Groningen===
Bacuna is a [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] youth exponent. He made his [[Eredivisie]] debut on 5 February 2015 against [[Heracles Almelo]] replacing [[Yoell van Nieff]] after 79 minutes in a 2–2 away draw.<ref name="soccerway2">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/02/05/netherlands/eredivisie/stichting-heracles-almelo/stichting-fc-groningen/1690849/|title=Heracles Almelo vs FC Groningen|work=Soccerway|publisher=Perform Group|date=5 February 2015|access-date=8 March 2015|archive-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620160140/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/02/05/netherlands/eredivisie/stichting-heracles-almelo/stichting-fc-groningen/1690849/|url-status=live}}</ref> He came off the bench to help the Green-White Army win the [[KNVB Cup]] in the 2014–15 season against defending champions [[PEC Zwolle]]. It was their first major trophy and they qualified for the [[UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Groningen claim first trophy with KNVB Cup triumph|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/462/netherlands/2015/05/04/11389992/groningen-claim-first-trophy-with-knvb-cup-triumph|access-date=18 May 2015|work=Goal.com|date=4 May 2015|archive-date=24 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324154917/https://www.goal.com/en/news/462/netherlands/2015/05/04/11389992/groningen-claim-first-trophy-with-knvb-cup-triumph|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/05/03/netherlands/knvb-beker/bvo-fc-zwolle/stichting-fc-groningen/2028581/|title=PEC Zwolle vs. Groningen|work=Soccerway|publisher=Perform Group|date=3 May 2015|access-date=25 March 2021|archive-date=15 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210415083533/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/05/03/netherlands/knvb-beker/bvo-fc-zwolle/stichting-fc-groningen/2028581/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Huddersfield Town===
Bacuna signed for [[Premier League]] team [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] on 20 June 2018, for an undisclosed fee for three years, with the club having the option for a further season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11410829/huddersfield-sign-juninho-bacuna-from-fc-groningen|title=Huddersfield sign Juninho Bacuna from FC Groningen|publisher=Sky Sports|date=20 June 2018|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621170715/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11410829/huddersfield-sign-juninho-bacuna-from-fc-groningen|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 27 October 2018, Bacuna made his debut in the Premier League in a 3–0 away defeat to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], coming on as a 78th-minute substitute.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Watford 3–0 Huddersfield: Defeat sends Terriers to bottom of table|date=27 October 2018|publisher=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45924060|access-date=26 May 2021|archive-date=30 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230430175953/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45924060|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March 2019, he scored his first goal for Huddersfield in a 4–3 defeat at [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=West Ham 4–3 Huddersfield: Javier Hernandez double rescues West Ham|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 March 2019|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47505640|access-date=26 May 2021|archive-date=27 November 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221127043449/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47505640|url-status=live}}</ref>

After relegation from the Premier League, Huddersfield started the 2019–20 season in the [[EFL Championship]] badly, only amassing two points from their first nine games. Bacuna scored the only goal in the game in Huddersfield's first win of the season over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on 1 October 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=Huddersfield beat bottom side Stoke|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 October 2019|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49805862|access-date=26 May 2021|archive-date=13 November 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221113094205/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49805862|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 11 May 2021, Huddersfield exercised the option to extend Bacuna's contract until the end of the 2021–22 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Retained List Confirmed|url=https://www.htafc.com/news/2021/may/retained-list-confirmed/|access-date=26 May 2021|publisher=Huddersfield Town AFC|date=11 May 2021|first=Adam|last=Tomlinson|archive-date=14 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514025821/https://www.htafc.com/news/2021/may/retained-list-confirmed/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Rangers ===
On 19 August 2021, Bacuna signed for [[Scottish Premiership]] team [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11788/12385527/rangers-transfer-news-juninho-bacuna-joins-scottish-champions-from-huddersfield |title=Rangers transfer news: Juninho Bacuna joins Scottish champions from Huddersfield |website=Sky Sports |date=20 August 2021 |access-date=19 March 2022 |archive-date=6 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221006200824/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11788/12385527/rangers-transfer-news-juninho-bacuna-joins-scottish-champions-from-huddersfield |url-status=live }}</ref> The player was paraded to the club's supporters during the half-time interval of Rangers' [[2021–22 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round|Europa League play-off]] game against [[FC Alashkert|Alashkert]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Report: Morelos Goal Gives 10-Man Gers The Win|url=https://www.rangers.co.uk/article/report-morelos-goal-gives-10-man-gers-the-win/s3xyl9jjvzT7gQMtBCp5Q|access-date=19 August 2021|publisher=Rangers FC|date=19 August 2021|first=Nick|last=Thomson|archive-date=4 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221004142522/https://www.rangers.co.uk/article/report-morelos-goal-gives-10-man-gers-the-win/s3xyl9jjvzT7gQMtBCp5Q|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Birmingham City===
Bacuna returned to English football when he joined Championship club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 27 January 2022 on a three-and-a-half-year contract; the fee was undisclosed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/juninho-bacuna-leaves-rangers-to-sign-for-birmingham-city |title=Juninho Bacuna leaves Rangers to sign for Birmingham City |first=Andy |last=Coyle |publisher=STV |date=27 January 2022 |access-date=6 July 2024 |archive-date=6 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706164631/https://news.stv.tv/sport/juninho-bacuna-leaves-rangers-to-sign-for-birmingham-city |url-status=live }}</ref> He scored his first Birmingham goal in a 3–0 win at home to [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] on 12 February,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60268852 |title=Birmingham City 3–0 Luton Town 0 |website=BBC Sport |date=12 February 2022 |access-date=23 February 2022 |archive-date=1 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231101141233/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60268852 |url-status=live }}</ref> and finished the season with two goals and three assists from 17 appearances.<ref name=sb2122 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-rangers-bacuna-juninho-23853469 |title=Juninho Bacuna opens up about life at Birmingham City following Rangers exit |first=Brian |last=Dick |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=3 May 2022 |access-date=6 July 2024 |archive-date=6 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706164638/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-rangers-bacuna-juninho-23853469 |url-status=live }}</ref>

At the start of the 2022–23 season new head coach [[John Eustace]] impressed on Bacuna that there was no doubt as to his exceptional talent with the ball but he needed to combine that with hard work off the ball, particularly in a small squad "over-reliant on [him] to create goal scoring opportunities".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-juninho-bacuna-eustace-24789409 |title=Birmingham City boss John Eustace reveals Juninho Bacuna talks |first=Brian |last=Dick |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=18 August 2022 |access-date=6 July 2024 |archive-date=22 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230122120233/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-juninho-bacuna-eustace-24789409 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-talking-points-blues-24744789 |title=Birmingham City talking points as Blues face reality check after Cardiff City defeat |first=Bruna |last=Reis |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=14 August 2022 |access-date=6 July 2024 |archive-date=6 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706164629/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-talking-points-blues-24744789 |url-status=live }}</ref> By October he was filling in at [[wing back (association football)|wing back]], from which position he scored a goal-of-the-season candidate away to [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-hull-25276405 |title=Birmingham City player ratings vs Hull City: Deeney and Bacuna put Blues in the top half of the table |first=Brian |last=Dick |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=16 October 2022 |access-date=6 July 2024 |archive-date=6 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706164641/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-hull-25276405 |url-status=live }}</ref> As the season went on, his concentration improved and Eustace suggested he was maturing as a player. He missed 3 Championship matches through suspension,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/juninho-bacuna-birmingham-city-qpr-26490422 |title=Juninho Bacuna decision confirmed in Birmingham City team news for QPR |first=Alex |last=Dicken |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=17 March 2023 |access-date=6 July 2024 |archive-date=6 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706164636/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/juninho-bacuna-birmingham-city-qpr-26490422 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ended up with six assists from the remaining 43.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/team/stats/_/id/392/league/ENG.2/season/2022/view/scoring |title=Birmingham City Scoring Stats – 2022–23 |website=ESPN |access-date=6 July 2024 |archive-date=6 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240706164629/https://www.espn.co.uk/football/team/stats/_/id/392/league/ENG.2/season/2022/view/scoring |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Al-Wehda FC===
Bacuna signed for [[Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al-Wehda FC|Al-Wehda]] on 28 August 2024 for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/pages/en/media-article/juninho-bacuna-completes-move-from-blues |title=Juninho Bacuna completes move from Blues |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=28 August 2024 |access-date=28 August 2024}}</ref>

===Gaziantep===
On 11 July 2025, [[Gaziantep F.K.|Gaziantep]] announced the signing of Bacuna for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|title=JUNINHO BACUNA GAZİANTEP!|language=Turkish|url=https://www.gaziantepfk.org/haberler/transfer-juninho-bacuna-gazi-antep-te|website=gaziantepfk.org|date= 11 July 2025|access-date=3 February 2026}}</ref>

===Volendam (loan)===
On 3 February 2026, Bacuna joined [[Eredivisie]] side [[FC Volendam|Volendam]] on a half-a-year long loan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Middenveld versterkt met komst Juninho Bacuna|url=https://fcvolendam.nl/nieuws/middenveld-versterkt-met-komst-juninho-bacuna/|language=Dutch|website=fcvoldendam.nl|date= 3 February 2026|access-date=3 February 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Bacuna represented his native Netherlands at under-18, under-20 and [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|under-21 levels]]. He played eleven matches for the under-20s, and three for the under-21s, and scored twice in a 4–1 win against [[Bolivia national under-20 football team|Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/206598/speler/518 |title=Juninho Bacuna: Jeugd mannen beloftenelftal |website=OnsOranje |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231031180826/https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/206598/speler/518 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/toernooien/2070/selectie/185185/speler/518 |title=Juninho Bacuna: Jong Oranje |website=OnsOranje |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231031173840/https://www.onsoranje.nl/toernooien/2070/selectie/185185/speler/518 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/toernooien/8110/wedstrijd/30679 |title=Oefeninterlands, Seizoen 2017/'18: Jong Bolivia 1–4 Jong Oranje |website=OnsOranje |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=6 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221006185956/https://www.onsoranje.nl/toernooien/8110/wedstrijd/30679 |url-status=live }}</ref>

He switched to represent [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao]], for which he qualified by descent, in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.htafc.com/news/2019/september/bacuna-on-playing-for-his-home-country/ |title=Bacuna on playing for his home country |first=Mikey |last=Partington |publisher=Huddersfield Town A.F.C. |date=3 September 2019 |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=7 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230607123149/https://www.htafc.com/news/2019/september/bacuna-on-playing-for-his-home-country/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He played four matches in that year's [[2019–20 CONCACAF Nations League A#Group D|CONCACAF Nations League A group stage]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe376716/juninho-bacuna/ |title=Juninho Bacuna: CONCACAF Nations League A 2019/2020 |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HeimSpiel Medien |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231031175611/https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/juninho-bacuna/concacaf-nations-league-2019-2020/curacao-team/3/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and once international football resumed after the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], continued as a regular in the team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe376716/juninho-bacuna/international-matches/ |title=Juninho Bacuna: Internationals |website=worldfootball.net |publisher=HeimSpiel Medien |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=31 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231031174439/https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/juninho-bacuna/4/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In September 2022, Bacuna played two friendly matches for Curaçao against the [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia national team]] in Indonesia. In the first, he scored in a 3–2 defeat.<ref name="Int Soccerway">{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/juninho-bacuna/395770/ |title=J. Bacuna |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=10 April 2025}}</ref> In the second, he was [[sent off]] after receiving a second yellow card for a bad tackle on [[Marselino Ferdinan]]. He reacted to the dismissal by kicking the ball towards spectators, who retaliated by throwing water bottles onto the pitch. After the match, Bacuna was targeted on social media with abusive messages, some of a racist nature. His club issued a statement condemning the abuse and confirmed that it had been reported to the social media platforms.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordot.app/949220781064224768 |title=Birmingham City's Juninho Bacuna Subjected to Social Media Abuse from Indonesia Fans |website=Football Tribe Asia |date=2 October 2022 |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=7 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221007103905/https://nordot.app/949220781064224768 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-statement-juninho-bacuna-25159892 |title=Birmingham City condemn racist abuse directed at Juninho Bacuna |first=Matt |last=Abbott |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=2 October 2022 |access-date=2 October 2022 |archive-date=18 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221018131714/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-statement-juninho-bacuna-25159892 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Bacuna is the younger brother fellow footballers [[Leandro Bacuna]] and [[Johnsen Bacuna]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2015-04-29 |title=Drie Bacuna-broers staan in bekerfinale |url=https://www.rtvnoord.nl/nieuws/148448/drie-bacuna-broers-staan-in-bekerfinale |access-date=2026-03-23 |website=www.rtvnoord.nl |language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ook tweede Bacuna wint de beker|trans-title=A second Bacuna wins the cup as well|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/2036079-ook-tweede-bacuna-wint-de-beker.html|access-date=6 November 2015|publisher=Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|date=17 May 2015|language=nl|archive-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304141223/http://nos.nl/artikel/2036079-ook-tweede-bacuna-wint-de-beker.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

